      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Oxygen is a colourless, odourless and tasteless gas, somewhat denser than air. Found in nature in two allotropic forms: as common oxygen, having diatomic molecules </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">– </text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">O</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0"> and as ozone, characterised by triatomic molecules  </text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">O</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">. The three known stable isotopes of oxygen are: </text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="16" fc="1163500" fs="b" fa="1" charset="0">16</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="16" fc="1163500" fs="b" fa="1" charset="238">O, </text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="16" fc="1163500" fs="b" fa="1" charset="0">17</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="16" fc="1163500" fs="b" fa="1" charset="238">O, </text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="16" fc="1163500" fs="b" fa="1" charset="0">18</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">O. Oxygen combines with nearly all elements. It is essential for almost all forms of life on our planet.  </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">It was first obtained in 1774 by the English chemist Joseph Priestley and, independently, by the Swedish chemist Karl Wilhelm Scheele. </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238"> Oxygen was recognised as an element by the French chemist Antoine Laurent Lavoisier in 1775. Its name is derived from the Greek words oxy - </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fs="i" fa="1" charset="238">acidic</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238"> and </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fs="i" fa="1" charset="238">genno</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238"> - produce.</text>
   </par>
